when it exploded in 1986?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I don't know about a RTG on that booster. Glance at the mission objectives doesn't show anything that likely would have one. I'll dig around later, and see what turns up -there's also vague references to the one from the Apollo-13 LEM being recovered, but nothing solid on that (a good research project for us...) <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &gt; I've heard someone say that the force of that<br>
explosion was equivalent to a low yield nuke, yet<br>
the pu was contained just as planned.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I do know that's wrong.<br>
 The H2/O2 was released, followed shortly by the hypergolics from the orbiters' RCS/OMS systems, and there was a  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://history.nasa.gov/rogersrep/v1ch3.htm">&quot;massive, almost explosive, burning&quot;</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
 A medical examiner who looked at the data and the wreckage of the crew cabin (I don't know if he was involved in any post-mortems, if any) said that the forces on the crew cabin weren't enough to kill the 7 (At least, we're 99.999% certain that it didn't kill all of them. They did say that impact with the ocean or the seabed didn't turn on the emergency air supplies).<br>
<br>
His <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/kerwin.html">report</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->:<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   The largest acceleration pulse occurred as the Orbiter forward fuselage separated and was rapidly pushed away from the external tank. It then pitched nose-down and was decelerated rapidly by aerodynamic forces... The range of most probable maximum accelerations is from 12 to 20 G's in the vertical axis. These accelerations were quite brief. In two seconds, they were below four G's; in less than ten seconds, the crew compartment was essentially in free fall. Medical analysis indicates that these accelerations are survivable, and that the probability of major injury to crew members is low. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 That's part of why the hysteria about the Cassini launch was bogus. A water tank from the Skylab was found nearly intact on the ground when it fell from orbit -far less stress than from a booster malfunction, and it's most likely that the crew of the Challenger survived until they hit the water. How likely that a properly designed RTG -or even the shipping container atop a HLV with the NPR pulse units aboard- would not &quot;spread vaporised Pu over the Earth&quot;, or even crack open?<br>
 Yeah, that water tank was pretty beat up. A shipping container with the pits of the pulse units would probably not be in good shape either, but would it threaten anything that wasn't already crushed when it hit? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 6/2/02 7:45:44 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 111<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/2/02 7:55:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: &quot;Hysteria mongers&quot; mischaracterized?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Others, such as Dr. John Pike, DO, in fact,<br>
