<br>
 I humbly retract my earlier poorly considered broadbrush characterization.<br>
<br>
 There most certainly are some who have cares about the possible dangers of radioactives on spacecraft who aren't raving fringe lunatics.<br>
<br>
 Does Dr Pike write anything about the amount of Pu aboard the probe being vaporised across the globe, and killing bilions?<br>
 If so, then he'd better have some good numbers to show  (every step of the way, from the booster &amp; range safety charges explosions, to the inhalation of and mortality caused by the particles). If not, then he should be careful who he associates with, or maybe be a moderating influence on their hysteria mongering. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 130<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/24/02 1:58:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Protecting the Pu from launch accident</span><hr size=1> Yale<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt;... it is typically by swingby re-entries that Pu238<br>
dispersion occurs (RTGs are -NOT- designed to survive<br>
them). Safety is based not on RTG design, but on<br>
careful trajectories.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Name one Earth swingby that's missed its mark and re-entered and done this? Some sub-orbital and orbital re-entry accidents have dispersed radioactives (second or upper stage failures). No interplanetary ones have -the infamous Cassini swingby barely missed its mark above the Earth by 4 miles after several trips around the Sun. (Just double check any figures you get from Lock-Mart, who still uses measuring units from the dark ages.)<br>
 I'll suggest that the RTGs which have dispersed radioactives in the atmosphere had no particular safety considerations. Has anybody tried taking the responsible nations to task in coourts of law over the provisions in the space treaties?<br>
 That's obviously not the way to build it.<br>
<br>
cattlecar<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; I am against swingby trajectories of RTG powered<br>
craft past the Earth.<br>
&gt; Therefore I am an advocate of more powerful boosters,<br>
and nuclear propulsion space systems to eliminate the<br>
need for gravity assists.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Good point there. We either launch it in one shot (if the 'clean' or 'fusion only' pulse units become available and palatable) or we assemble it in space, use something benign to boost it above the VanAllen belts, and send it on its way without the need for gravity assists.<br>
<br>
Looking at the old design for the 10 meter ship, I'm not sure about the total fuel mass. I suspect it's ~200 tons (which means 100 tons for the engine and basic structure, 200 tons for propellant, and the rest (~280 tons) cargo. (With refueling at the destination, we delete 90 tons of propellant from the return delta-V thrust bombs. This extra mass doesn't need to be lifted from Earth, or can be outbound cargo.)<br>
 That's about 20 tons to orbit, for just the Pu pits of the thrust bombs. They'll be loaded into the thrust bomb bodies, with propellant added in orbit. (<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>very</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> hazy numbers. Anybody feel free to generate more accurate estimates of the Pu mass...)<br>
<br>
 One &quot;Ares&quot; HLV shot gives us around 80 tons of protective packaging fo the Pu going up. That should be a hell of an armoured escape rocket to save the extremely valuable Pu from falling to the bottom of the ocean if the launcher goes &quot;boom&quot;. We could probably accept the cheapest &amp; simplest HLV for this shipment: the 2 SSME Shuttle-C puts about 47 tons up, and that should allow for enough protection.<br>
<br>
 What I'm trying to show is that there's no reason to outright eliminate NPR from consideration -even old fashioned fission-bomb Orion.<br>
(Snide comments about hysteria aside) We can get around the present political distaste for Orion with some engineering -probably easier than tinkering NEP or Magsails up to the performance needed to seriously compete with Orion (and they've got a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> hell of a long way to go</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to beat Orion).<br>
<br>
 It's the simplest way to get the amounts of performance we need for interplanetary flight, whether the considerations are crew safety or timely profitability.<br>
<br>
<br>
Looking around, I see that the old Sea Dragon HLV puts 550 tons into LEO. That's the entire 10 meter ship into LEO (fission free) in one shot. Loft the Pu pits on another specially prepared booster (provide an escape vehicle for the crew on the ship itself?), and the mission is off on its way.<br>
Another idea: the Sea Dragon could probably put the 20 meter ship above the atmosphere from a floating platform in the Pacific ocean. We don't know the mass of that ship, but I'll guestimate ~2500 tons. Consider that the second generation, after the little 10 meter ships have opened the way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 186<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/24/02 2:09:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Sea Dragon</span><hr size=1> I like the Sea Dragon idea.  I like it even better if it launched the components for a 4000 ton Orion in what, 8 seperate Sea Dragon launches, then assembled in orbit  Orion really works best as a big ship.<br>
